@startuml MultiServerIdempotentWithCache

title Idempotent POST - Multi-Server Setup with Replication Lag\nSolution: Distributed Cache (Redis) for Fast Key Replication

skinparam backgroundColor #FAFAFA
skinparam ArrowColor #555555
skinparam NoteBackgroundColor #FFFDE7
skinparam NoteBorderColor #F9A825
skinparam SequenceGroupBackgroundColor #F3F9FF
skinparam SequenceGroupBorderColor #4A90D9
skinparam SequenceBoxBackgroundColor #EEF7EE
skinparam SequenceBoxBorderColor #5A9E5A

autonumber

actor "Client" as client
participant "Load Balancer" as lb

box "Server Cluster" #EEF7EE
  participant "App Server 1" as s1
  participant "App Server 2" as s2
  participant "App Server 3" as s3
end box

box "Shared Distributed Cache" #FFF8E1
  database "Redis Cache\n(Primary)" as redisPrimary
  database "Redis Replica 1" as redisReplica1
  database "Redis Replica 2" as redisReplica2
end box

box "Independent Databases (per server)" #F3F9FF
  database "DB 1\n(Server 1)" as db1
  database "DB 2\n(Server 2)" as db2
  database "DB 3\n(Server 3)" as db3
end box

' ─────────────────────────────────────────
== PROBLEM CONTEXT: DB Replication Lag ==
' ─────────────────────────────────────────

note over db1, db3
  Each server has its own DB.
  DB replication is ASYNC and can lag by seconds/minutes.
  If Server 1 writes to DB1, Server 2 may not see it yet.
  This breaks idempotency when retry hits a different server!
end note

' ─────────────────────────────────────────
== FIRST REQUEST: Client sends POST (hits Server 1) ==
' ─────────────────────────────────────────

client -> lb : POST /orders\nIdempotency-Key: uuid-abc123\n(body: item=A, qty=1)
lb -> s1 : Route to Server 1

s1 -> s1 : Validate Idempotency-Key header present

note right of s1
  Step 1: Check CACHE first (not DB).
  Cache replication is near-instant
  across all Redis nodes (<1ms).
end note

s1 -> redisPrimary : GET idempotency:uuid-abc123
redisPrimary -> s1 : NIL (key not found)

s1 -> redisPrimary : SET idempotency:uuid-abc123\nstatus=CREATED\nEX 86400 (TTL: 24h)\n[ATOMIC SETNX]

note right of redisPrimary
  SETNX = SET if Not eXists
  Atomic operation - prevents
  race condition at cache level.
end note

redisPrimary -> s1 : OK

s1 -> db1 : INSERT order\n(item=A, qty=1)
db1 -> s1 : OK (order_id=601)

s1 -> redisPrimary : SET idempotency:uuid-abc123\nstatus=CONSUMED\nresponse={order_id:601, code:201}\nEX 86400

redisPrimary -> s1 : OK

s1 -> client : HTTP 201 Created\n{order_id: 601}

' ─────────────────────────────────────────
== CACHE REPLICATION (near-instant) ==
' ─────────────────────────────────────────

redisPrimary ->> redisReplica1 : ASYNC REPLICATE\nidempotency:uuid-abc123\nstatus=CONSUMED
redisPrimary ->> redisReplica2 : ASYNC REPLICATE\nidempotency:uuid-abc123\nstatus=CONSUMED

note over redisPrimary, redisReplica2
  Redis replication lag: <1ms (sub-millisecond).
  All replicas are updated almost instantly.
  Contrast with DB replication: can lag seconds/minutes.
end note

' ─────────────────────────────────────────
== DB REPLICATION (slow, async background) ==
' ─────────────────────────────────────────

db1 ->> db2 : ASYNC DB REPLICATION\n(can lag seconds to minutes)
db1 ->> db3 : ASYNC DB REPLICATION\n(can lag seconds to minutes)

note over db1, db3 #F8CECC
  WARNING: DB replication has NOT completed yet.
  If retry hits Server 2 or 3 and checks DB directly,
  they would see NO record and process DUPLICATE order!
  This is why we MUST check cache, not DB.
end note

' ─────────────────────────────────────────
== RETRY REQUEST: Same client retries (hits Server 2) ==
' ─────────────────────────────────────────

client -> lb : POST /orders\nIdempotency-Key: uuid-abc123\n(body: item=A, qty=1)
lb -> s2 : Route to Server 2 (different server!)

s2 -> s2 : Validate Idempotency-Key header present

note right of s2
  Server 2 has NO knowledge of Server 1's processing.
  DB replication may still be in progress.
  Server 2 reads from Redis Replica (near-instant sync).
end note

s2 -> redisReplica1 : GET idempotency:uuid-abc123
redisReplica1 -> s2 : HIT! status=CONSUMED\nresponse={order_id:601, code:201}

s2 -> s2 : Key found + status=CONSUMED\nReturn cached response directly\nSkip DB entirely

s2 -> client : HTTP 200 OK\n{order_id: 601}\n(cached response — no duplicate created!)

note right of s2 #D5E8D4
  SUCCESS: Idempotency preserved!
  Server 2 did NOT touch DB2 at all.
  No duplicate order created.
  Cache was the source of truth.
end note

' ─────────────────────────────────────────
== PARALLEL CASE: Third request hits Server 3 during processing ==
' ─────────────────────────────────────────

group Bonus: Concurrent request during CREATED state
  client -> lb : POST /orders\nIdempotency-Key: uuid-abc123
  lb -> s3 : Route to Server 3
  s3 -> redisReplica2 : GET idempotency:uuid-abc123
  redisReplica2 -> s3 : HIT! status=CREATED\n(still processing on Server 1)
  s3 -> client : HTTP 409 Conflict\n{error: "Request already in progress,\nretry after a moment"}
end group

' ─────────────────────────────────────────

note over client, db3
  KEY DESIGN DECISIONS:
  1. Always check Redis cache BEFORE touching any DB
  2. Use Redis SETNX (atomic SET if Not eXists) to prevent race at cache level
  3. Cache TTL = 24h (matches idempotency window)
  4. status=CREATED  -> 409 Conflict (in-flight protection)
  5. status=CONSUMED -> 200 OK      (replay cached response)
  6. DB replication is irrelevant for idempotency — cache is the authority
end note

@enduml

